Class JsNavigator.Member

Enclosing class:
JsNavigator
public static class JsNavigator.Member
extends DOM.Navigator.Prototype.Member

An opaque class representing members of its enclosing opaque type.

Note that, this class is opaque but its constructors are all internal. This class and the subclasses of this class are used to declare either opaque public instance fields of the opaque type Var.Member or the opaque public static fields of other opaque types while their constructors are used to define the fields inside opaque classes. Under either circumstance, the field names must be exactly same as the member names, as the opaque fields of opaque types are resolved by re-compilers directly based on the field names.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org
JavaScript:
Opaque types can be resolved but no class objects for them can be created in the target codes. Re-compilers must exit with error on operations accessing that kind of class objects. Re-compilers must resolve an opaque instance field declared by this class in Var.Member or its subclasses to the JavaScript identifier: 
q.m
where m is the identifier of the field name and q is the identifier resolved from the instance of the enclosing member. Re-compilers must resolve an opaque static field declared by this class in opaque types other than Var.Member and its subclasses to the JavaScript identifier: 
m
where m is the identifier of the field name. And re-compilers must report error on the access to opaque fields declared by this class under any other circumstances.

Field Detail

appCodeName

public final Value.String.Member appCodeName

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsNavigator object refers to a read-only string that specifies the code name of the browser. In all browsers based on the Netscape code base (Netscape, Mozilla, Firefox), this is "Mozilla". For compatibility, this property is "Mozilla" in Microsoft browsers as well.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

appName

public final Value.String.Member appName

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsNavigator object refers to a read-only string that specifies the name of the browser. For Netscape-based browsers, the value of the property is "Netscape". In IE, the value of the property is "Microsoft Internet Explorer". Other browsers may identify themselves correctly or spoof another browser for compatibility.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

appVersion

public final Value.String.Member appVersion

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsNavigator object refers to a read-only string that specifies version and platform information for the browser. The first part of this string is a version number. Pass the string to Js.parseInt(Object) to obtain only the major version number or to Js.parseFloat(Object) to obtain the major and minor version numbers as a floating-point value. The remainder of the string value of the property provides other details about the browser version, including the operating system it is running on. Unfortunately, however, the format of this information varies widely from browser to browser.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

platform

public final Value.String.Member platform

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsNavigator object refers to a read-only string that specifies the operating system and/or hardware platform on which the browser is running. Although there is no standard set of values for this property, some typical values are "Win32", "MacPPC", and "Linux i586".

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

plugins

public final JsPlugin.Member plugins

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsNavigator object refers to an array of JsPlugin objects, each of which represents one plug-in that is installed in the browser. A JsPlugin object provides information about the plug-in, including a list of MIME types it supports. The array is defined by IE but is always empty because IE does not support the JsPlugin.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

userAgent

public final Value.String.Member userAgent

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsNavigator object refers to a read-only string that specifies the value the browser uses for the user-agent header in HTTP requests. Typically, this is the value of appCodeName followed by a slash and the value of appVersion.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

mimeTypes

public final JsArray.Member mimeTypes

An opaque instance field defining a sub-member that is named by the name of this field, qualified by the current member instance of the field, and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsNavigator object refers to an array of JsMimeType objects, each of which represents one of the MIME types (e.g., "text/html" and "image/gif") supported by the browser. This array may be indexed numerically or by the name of the MIME type. The array is defined by IEr but is always empty because IE does not support JsMimeType.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this instance field to the identifier of the field name appending to the identifier resolved from its qualifying member with a dot in between.

JsNavigator.Member

public JsNavigator.Member(JsObject.Member q,
                          Var.Mid mid)

Internally constructs a member based on a qualifying member.

This constructor is internal and only called inside of opaque or internal classes or class members.

Note that, this constructor is internal but its declaring class is opaque. This constructor is used to define opaque instance fields declared in the declaring class of this constructor itself or its subclasses. Under this circumstance, the field names must be exactly same as the member names, as the opaque instance fields of the opaque type Var.Member or its subclasses are resolved by re-compilers directly to their names appending to the name resolved from the specified qualifying member with a dot in between.

Parameters:
q - A qualifying member
mid - The ID of the member to construct
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must report error on the invocation to an internal constructor.
